# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: heroku-platform
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:heroku-platform/autoscaling] Autoscaling differs from having a fixed daily, weekly, or yearly cycle of server use in that it is responsive to actual usage patterns, and thus reduces the potential downside of having too few or too many servers for the traffic load.
[src:heroku-platform/autoscaling] For instance, if traffic is usually lower at midnight, then a static scaling solution might schedule some servers to sleep at night, but this might result in downtime on a night where people happen to use the Internet more (for instance, due to a viral news event).
[src:heroku-platform/autoscaling] Autoscaling, on the other hand, can handle unexpected traffic spikes better.
[src:heroku-platform/autoscaling] In the list below, we use the terminology used by Amazon Web Services (AWS).
[src:heroku-platform/autoscaling] However, alternative names are noted and terminology that is specific to the names of Amazon services is not used for the names.
[src:heroku-platform/autoscaling] Amazon Web Services launched the Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2) service in August 2006, that allowed developers to programmatically create and terminate instances (machines).
[src:heroku-platform/autoscaling] At the time of initial launch, AWS did not offer autoscaling, but the ability to programmatically create and terminate instances gave developers the flexibility to write their own code for autoscaling.
[src:heroku-platform/autoscaling] Third-party autoscaling software for AWS began appearing around April 2008.
[src:heroku-platform/autoscaling] These included tools by Scalr and RightScale.
[src:heroku-platform/autoscaling] RightScale was used by Animoto, which was able to handle Facebook traffic by adopting autoscaling.
[src:heroku-platform/autoscaling] On May 18, 2009, Amazon launched its own autoscaling feature along with Elastic Load Balancing, as part of Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud.
[src:heroku-platform/autoscaling] Autoscaling is now an integral component of Amazon's EC2 offering.
[src:heroku-platform/autoscaling] Autoscaling on Amazon Web Services is done through a web browser or the command line tool.
[src:heroku-platform/autoscaling] In May 2016 Autoscaling was also offered in AWS ECS Service.
[src:heroku-platform/autoscaling] On-demand video provider Netflix documented their use of autoscaling with Amazon Web Services to meet their highly variable consumer needs.
[src:heroku-platform/autoscaling] They found that aggressive scaling up and delayed and cautious scaling down served their goals of uptime and responsiveness best.
[src:heroku-platform/autoscaling] In an article for *TechCrunch*, Zev Laderman, the co-founder and CEO of Newvem, a service that helps optimize AWS cloud infrastructure, recommended that startups use autoscaling in order to keep their Amazon Web Services costs low.
[src:heroku-platform/autoscaling] Various best practice guides for AWS use suggest using its autoscaling feature even in cases where the load is not variable.
[src:heroku-platform/autoscaling] Netflix's internal best practices require every instance to be in an autoscaling group, and its conformity monkey terminates any instance not in an autoscaling group in order to enforce this best practice.
[src:heroku-platform/autoscaling] On June 27, 2013, Microsoft announced that it was adding autoscaling support to its Windows Azure cloud computing platform.
[src:heroku-platform/autoscaling] Documentation for the feature is available on the Microsoft Developer Network.
[src:heroku-platform/autoscaling] Oracle Cloud Platform allows server instances to automatically scale a cluster in or out by defining an auto-scaling rule.
[src:heroku-platform/autoscaling] These rules are based on CPU and/or memory utilization and determine when to add or remove nodes.
[src:heroku-platform/autoscaling] On November 17, 2014, the Google Compute Engine announced a public beta of its autoscaling feature for use in Google Cloud Platform applications.
[src:heroku-platform/autoscaling] As of March 2015, the autoscaling tool is still in Beta.
[src:heroku-platform/autoscaling] In a blog post in August 2014, a Facebook engineer disclosed that the company had started using autoscaling to bring down its energy costs.
[src:heroku-platform/autoscaling] The blog post reported a 27% decline in energy use for low traffic hours (around midnight) and a 10-15% decline in energy use over the typical 24-hour cycle.
[src:heroku-platform/autoscaling] Autoscaling by default uses *reactive* decision approach for dealing with traffic scaling: scaling only happens in response to real-time changes in metrics.
[src:heroku-platform/autoscaling] In some cases, particularly when the changes occur very quickly, this reactive approach to scaling is insufficient.
[src:heroku-platform/autoscaling] Two other kinds of autoscaling decision approaches are described below.
[src:heroku-platform/autoscaling] This is an approach to autoscaling where changes are made to the minimum size, maximum size, or desired capacity of the autoscaling group at specific times of day.
[src:heroku-platform/autoscaling] Scheduled scaling is useful, for instance, if there is a known traffic load increase or decrease at specific times of the day, but the change is too sudden for reactive approach based autoscaling to respond fast enough.
[src:heroku-platform/autoscaling] AWS autoscaling groups support scheduled scaling.
[src:heroku-platform/autoscaling] This approach to autoscaling uses predictive analytics.
[src:heroku-platform/autoscaling] The idea is to combine recent usage trends with historical usage data as well as other kinds of data to predict usage in the future, and autoscale based on these predictions.
[src:heroku-platform/autoscaling] For parts of their infrastructure and specific workloads, Netflix found that Scryer, their predictive analytics engine, gave better results than Amazon's reactive autoscaling approach.
[src:heroku-platform/autoscaling] On November 20, 2018, AWS announced that predictive scaling would be available as part of its autoscaling offering.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] In 2011, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) identified five "essential characteristics" for cloud systems.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] By 2023, the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) had expanded and refined the list.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] The history of cloud computing extends to the 1960s, with the initial concepts of time-sharing becoming popularized via remote job entry (RJE).
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] The "data center" model, where users submitted jobs to operators to run on mainframes, was predominantly used during this era.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] This period saw broad experimentation with making large-scale computing power more accessible through time-sharing, while optimizing infrastructure, platforms, and applications to improve efficiency for end users.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] The "cloud" metaphor for virtualized services dates to 1994, when it was used by General Magic for the universe of "places" that mobile agents in the Telescript environment could "go".
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] The metaphor is credited to David Hoffman, a General Magic communications specialist, based on its long-standing use in networking and telecom.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] The expression *cloud computing* became more widely known in 1996 when Compaq Computer Corporation drew up a business plan for future computing and the Internet.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] The company's ambition was to supercharge sales with "cloud computing-enabled applications".
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] The business plan foresaw that online consumer file storage would likely be commercially successful.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] As a result, Compaq decided to sell server hardware to internet service providers.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] In the 2000s, the application of cloud computing began to take shape with the establishment of Amazon Web Services (AWS) in 2002, which allowed developers to build applications independently.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] In 2006 Amazon Simple Storage Service, known as Amazon S3, and the Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2) were released.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] In 2008 NASA's development of the first open-source software for deploying private and hybrid clouds.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] The following decade saw the launch of various cloud services.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] In 2010, Microsoft launched Microsoft Azure, and Rackspace Hosting and NASA initiated an open-source cloud-software project, OpenStack.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] IBM introduced the IBM SmartCloud framework in 2011, and Oracle announced the Oracle Cloud in 2012.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] In December 2019, Amazon launched AWS Outposts, a service that extends AWS infrastructure, services, APIs, and tools to customer data centers, co-location spaces, or on-premises facilities.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Cloud computing can shorten time to market by offering pre-configured tools, scalable resources, and managed services, allowing users to focus on core business value rather than maintaining infrastructure.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Cloud platforms can enable organizations and individuals to reduce upfront capital expenditures on physical infrastructure by shifting to an operational expenditure model, where costs scale with usage.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Cloud platforms also offer managed services and tools, such as artificial intelligence, data analytics, and machine learning, which might otherwise require significant in-house expertise and infrastructure investment.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] While cloud computing can offer cost advantages through effective resource optimization, organizations often face challenges such as unused resources, inefficient configurations, and hidden costs without proper oversight and governance.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Many cloud platforms provide cost management tools, such as AWS Cost Explorer and Azure Cost Management, and frameworks like FinOps have emerged to standardize financial operations in the cloud.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Cloud computing also facilitates collaboration, remote work, and global service delivery by enabling secure access to data and applications from any location with an internet connection.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Cloud providers offer various redundancy options for core services, such as managed storage and managed databases, though redundancy configurations often vary by service tier.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Advanced redundancy strategies, such as cross-region replication or failover systems, typically require explicit configuration and may incur additional costs or licensing fees.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Cloud environments operate under a shared responsibility model, where providers are typically responsible for infrastructure security, physical hardware, and software updates, while customers are accountable for data encryption, identity and access management (IAM), and application-level security.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] The decision to adopt cloud computing or maintain on-premises infrastructure depends on factors such as scalability, cost structure, latency requirements, regulatory constraints, and infrastructure customization.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Organizations with variable or unpredictable workloads, limited capital for upfront investments, or a focus on rapid scalability benefit from cloud adoption.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Startups, SaaS companies, and e-commerce platforms often prefer the pay-as-you-go operational expenditure (OpEx) model of cloud infrastructure.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Additionally, companies prioritizing global accessibility, remote workforce enablement, disaster recovery, and leveraging advanced services such as AI/ML and analytics are well-suited for the cloud.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] In recent years, some cloud providers have started offering specialized services for high-performance computing and low-latency applications, addressing some use cases previously exclusive to on-premises setups.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] On the other hand, organizations with strict regulatory requirements, highly predictable workloads, or reliance on deeply integrated legacy systems may find cloud infrastructure less suitable.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Businesses in industries like defense, government, or those handling highly sensitive data often favor on-premises setups for greater control and data sovereignty.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Additionally, companies with ultra-low latency requirements, such as high-frequency trading (HFT) firms, rely on custom hardware (e.g., FPGAs) and physical proximity to exchanges, which most cloud providers cannot fully replicate despite recent advancements.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Similarly, tech giants like Google, Meta, and Amazon build their own data centers due to economies of scale, predictable workloads, and the ability to customize hardware and network infrastructure for optimal efficiency.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] However, these companies also use cloud services selectively for certain workloads and applications where it aligns with their operational needs.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] In practice, many organizations are increasingly adopting hybrid cloud architectures, combining on-premises infrastructure with cloud services.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] This approach allows businesses to balance scalability, cost-effectiveness, and control, offering the benefits of both deployment models while mitigating their respective limitations.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] One of the primary challenges of cloud computing, compared with traditional on-premises systems, is maintaining data security and privacy.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Cloud users entrust their sensitive data to third-party providers, who may not have adequate measures to protect it from unauthorized access, breaches, or leaks.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Cloud users also face compliance risks if they have to adhere to certain regulations or standards regarding data protection, such as GDPR or HIPAA.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Another challenge of cloud computing is reduced visibility and control.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Cloud users may not have full insight into how their cloud resources are managed, configured, or optimized by their providers.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] They may also have limited ability to customize or modify their cloud services according to their specific needs or preferences.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Complete understanding of all technology may be impossible, especially given the scale, complexity, and deliberate opacity of contemporary systems; however, there is a need for understanding complex technologies and their interconnections to have power and agency within them.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] The metaphor of the cloud can be seen as problematic as cloud computing retains the aura of something noumenal and numinous; it is something experienced without precisely understanding what it is or how it works.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Additionally, cloud migration is a significant challenge.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] This process involves transferring data, applications, or workloads from one cloud environment to another, or from on-premises infrastructure to the cloud.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Cloud migration can be complicated, time-consuming, and expensive, particularly when there are compatibility issues between different cloud platforms or architectures.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] If not carefully planned and executed, cloud migration can lead to downtime, reduced performance, or even data loss.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Applications hosted in the cloud are susceptible to the fallacies of distributed computing, a series of misconceptions that can lead to significant issues in software development and deployment.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] In a report by Gartner, a survey of 200 IT leaders revealed that 69% experienced budget overruns in their organizations' cloud expenditures during 2023.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Conversely, 31% of IT leaders whose organizations stayed within budget attributed their success to accurate forecasting and budgeting, proactive monitoring of spending, and effective optimization.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] The 2024 Flexera State of Cloud Report identifies the top cloud challenges as managing cloud spend, followed by security concerns and lack of expertise.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Public cloud expenditures exceeded budgeted amounts by an average of 15%.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] The report also reveals that cost savings is the top cloud initiative for 60% of respondents.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Furthermore, 65% measure cloud progress through cost savings, while 42% prioritize shorter time-to-market, indicating that cloud's promise of accelerated deployment is often overshadowed by cost concerns.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Typically, cloud providers' Service Level Agreements (SLAs) do not encompass all forms of service interruptions.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Exclusions typically include planned maintenance, downtime resulting from external factors such as network issues, human errors, like misconfigurations, natural disasters, force majeure events, or security breaches.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Typically, customers bear the responsibility of monitoring SLA compliance and must file claims for any unmet SLAs within a designated timeframe.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Customers should be aware of how deviations from SLAs are calculated, as these parameters may vary by service.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] These requirements can place a considerable burden on customers.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Additionally, SLA percentages and conditions can differ across various services within the same provider, with some services lacking any SLA altogether.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] In cases of service interruptions due to hardware failures in the cloud provider, the company typically does not offer monetary compensation.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Instead, eligible users may receive credits as outlined in the corresponding SLA.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Cloud computing abstractions aim to simplify resource management, but leaky abstractions can expose underlying complexities.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] These variations in abstraction quality depend on the cloud vendor, service and architecture.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Mitigating leaky abstractions requires users to understand the implementation details and limitations of the cloud services they utilize.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Service lock-in within the same vendor occurs when a customer becomes dependent on specific services within a cloud vendor, making it challenging to switch to alternative services within the same vendor when their needs change.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Cloud computing poses privacy concerns because the service provider can access the data that is in the cloud at any time.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] It could accidentally or deliberately alter or delete information.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Many cloud providers can share information with third parties if necessary for purposes of law and order without a warrant.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] That is permitted in their privacy policies, which users must agree to before they start using cloud services.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Solutions to privacy include policy and legislation as well as end-users' choices for how data is stored.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Users can encrypt data that is processed or stored within the cloud to prevent unauthorized access.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Identity management systems can also provide practical solutions to privacy concerns in cloud computing.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] These systems distinguish between authorized and unauthorized users and determine the amount of data that is accessible to each entity.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] The systems work by creating and describing identities, recording activities, and getting rid of unused identities.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] According to the Cloud Security Alliance, the top three threats in the cloud are *Insecure Interfaces and APIs*, *Data Loss & Leakage*, and *Hardware Failure*—which accounted for 29%, 25% and 10% of all cloud security outages respectively.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Together, these form shared technology vulnerabilities.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] In a cloud provider platform being shared by different users, there may be a possibility that information belonging to different customers resides on the same data server.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Additionally, Eugene Schultz, chief technology officer at Emagined Security, said that hackers are spending substantial time and effort looking for ways to penetrate the cloud.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] "There are some real Achilles' heels in the cloud infrastructure that are making big holes for the bad guys to get into".
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Because data from hundreds or thousands of companies can be stored on large cloud servers, hackers can theoretically gain control of huge stores of information through a single attack—a process he called "hyperjacking".
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Some examples of this include the Dropbox security breach, and iCloud 2014 leak.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Dropbox had been breached in October 2014, having over seven million of its users passwords stolen by hackers in an effort to get monetary value from it by Bitcoins (BTC).
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] By having these passwords, they are able to read private data as well as have this data be indexed by search engines (making the information public).
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] There is the problem of legal ownership of the data (If a user stores some data in the cloud, can the cloud provider profit from it?).
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Many Terms of Service agreements are silent on the question of ownership.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Physical control of the computer equipment (private cloud) is more secure than having the equipment off-site and under someone else's control (public cloud).
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] This delivers great incentive to public cloud computing service providers to prioritize building and maintaining strong management of secure services.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Some small businesses that do not have expertise in IT security could find that it is more secure for them to use a public cloud.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] There is the risk that end users do not understand the issues involved when signing on to a cloud service (persons sometimes do not read the many pages of the terms of service agreement, and just click "Accept" without reading).
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] This is important now that cloud computing is common and required for some services to work, for example for an intelligent personal assistant (Apple's Siri or Google Assistant).
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Fundamentally, private cloud is seen as more secure with higher levels of control for the owner, however public cloud is seen to be more flexible and requires less time and money investment from the user.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] The attacks that can be made on cloud computing systems include man-in-the middle attacks, phishing attacks, authentication attacks, and malware attacks.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] One of the largest threats is considered to be malware attacks, such as Trojan horses.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Recent research conducted in 2022 has revealed that the Trojan horse injection method is a serious problem with harmful impacts on cloud computing systems.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] The CLOUD Act allows United States authorities to request data from cloud providers, and courts can impose nondisclosure requirements preventing providers from notifying affected users.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] This framework is in legal tension with Article 48 of the European General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which restricts the transfer of personal data in response to foreign court or administrative orders unless based on an international agreement.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] As a result, cloud service providers operating in both Europe and the U.S. may face competing legal obligations.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Donohue writing for the *Harvard Journal of Law and Public Policy*, cloud service providers also fall within the broader category of service providers subject to Section 702 of the Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act (FISA), which has had documented effects on cloud providers and their customers.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] The National Institute of Standards and Technology recognized three cloud service models in 2011: Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), Platform as a Service (PaaS), and Software as a Service (SaaS).
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] The International Organization for Standardization (ISO) later identified additional models in 2023, including "Network as a Service", "Communications as a Service", "Compute as a Service", and "Data Storage as a Service".
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Infrastructure as a service (IaaS) refers to online services that provide high-level APIs used to abstract various low-level details of underlying network infrastructure like physical computing resources, location, data partitioning, scaling, security, backup, etc.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] A hypervisor runs the virtual machines as guests.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Pools of hypervisors within the cloud operational system can support large numbers of virtual machines and the ability to scale services up and down according to customers' varying requirements.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Linux containers run in isolated partitions of a single Linux kernel running directly on the physical hardware.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Linux cgroups and namespaces are the underlying Linux kernel technologies used to isolate, secure and manage the containers.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] The use of containers offers higher performance than virtualization because there is no hypervisor overhead.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] IaaS clouds often offer additional resources such as a virtual-machine disk-image library, raw block storage, file or object storage, firewalls, load balancers, IP addresses, virtual local area networks (VLANs), and software bundles.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] The NIST's definition of cloud computing describes IaaS as "where the consumer is able to deploy and run arbitrary software, which can include operating systems and applications.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] IaaS-cloud providers supply these resources on-demand from their large pools of equipment installed in data centers.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] For wide-area connectivity, customers can use either the Internet or carrier clouds (dedicated virtual private networks).
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] To deploy their applications, cloud users install operating-system images and their application software on the cloud infrastructure.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] In this model, the cloud user patches and maintains the operating systems and the application software.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Cloud providers typically bill IaaS services on a utility computing basis: cost reflects the number of resources allocated and consumed.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] PaaS vendors offer a development environment to application developers.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] The provider typically develops toolkit and standards for development and channels for distribution and payment.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] In the PaaS models, cloud providers deliver a computing platform, typically including an operating system, programming-language execution environment, database, and the web server.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Application developers develop and run their software on a cloud platform instead of directly buying and managing the underlying hardware and software layers.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] With some PaaS, the underlying computer and storage resources scale automatically to match application demand so that the cloud user does not have to allocate resources manually.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Some integration and data management providers also use specialized applications of PaaS as delivery models for data.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Examples include **iPaaS (Integration Platform as a Service)** and **dPaaS (Data Platform as a Service)**. iPaaS enables customers to develop, execute and govern integration flows.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Under the iPaaS integration model, customers drive the development and deployment of integrations without installing or managing any hardware or middleware. dPaaS delivers integration—and data-management—products as a fully managed service.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Under the dPaaS model, the PaaS provider, not the customer, manages the development and execution of programs by building data applications for the customer. dPaaS users access data through data-visualization tools.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] In the software as a service (SaaS) model, users gain access to application software and databases.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Cloud providers manage the infrastructure and platforms that run the applications.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] SaaS is sometimes referred to as "on-demand software" and is usually priced on a pay-per-use basis or using a subscription fee.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] In the SaaS model, cloud providers install and operate application software in the cloud and cloud users access the software from cloud clients.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Cloud users do not manage the cloud infrastructure and platform where the application runs.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] This eliminates the need to install and run the application on the cloud user's own computers, which simplifies maintenance and support.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Cloud applications differ from other applications in their scalability—which can be achieved by cloning tasks onto multiple virtual machines at run-time to meet changing work demand.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Load balancers distribute the work over the set of virtual machines.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] This process is transparent to the cloud user, who sees only a single access-point.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] To accommodate a large number of cloud users, cloud applications can be *multitenant*, meaning that any machine may serve more than one cloud-user organization.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] The pricing model for SaaS applications is typically a monthly or yearly flat fee per user, so prices become scalable and adjustable if users are added or removed at any point.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Proponents claim that SaaS gives a business the potential to reduce IT operational costs by outsourcing hardware and software maintenance and support to the cloud provider.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] This enables the business to reallocate IT operations costs away from hardware/software spending and from personnel expenses, towards meeting other goals.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] In addition, with applications hosted centrally, updates can be released without the need for users to install new software.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] One drawback of SaaS comes with storing the users' data on the cloud provider's server.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] As a result, there could be unauthorized access to the data.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Examples of applications offered as SaaS are games and productivity software like Google Docs and Office Online.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] SaaS applications may be integrated with cloud storage or File hosting services, which is the case with Google Docs being integrated with Google Drive, and Office Online being integrated with OneDrive.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Serverless computing allows customers to use various cloud capabilities without the need to provision, deploy, or manage hardware or software resources, apart from providing their application code or data.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] ISO/IEC 22123-2:2023 classifies serverless alongside Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), Platform as a Service (PaaS), and Software as a Service (SaaS) under the broader category of cloud service categories.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Notably, while ISO refers to these classifications as cloud service categories, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) refers to them as service models.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] "A cloud deployment model represents the way in which cloud computing can be organized based on the control and sharing of physical or virtual resources." Cloud deployment models define the fundamental patterns of interaction between cloud customers and cloud providers.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] They do not detail implementation specifics or the configuration of resources.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Private cloud is cloud infrastructure operated solely for a single organization, whether managed internally or by a third party, and hosted either internally or externally.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Undertaking a private cloud project requires significant engagement to virtualize the business environment, and requires the organization to reevaluate decisions about existing resources.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] It can improve business, but every step in the project raises security issues that must be addressed to prevent serious vulnerabilities.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Self-run data centers are generally capital intensive.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] They have a significant physical footprint, requiring allocations of space, hardware, and environmental controls.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] These assets have to be refreshed periodically, resulting in additional capital expenditures.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] They have attracted criticism because users "still have to buy, build, and manage them" and thus do not benefit from less hands-on management, essentially "[lacking] the economic model that makes cloud computing such an intriguing concept".
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Cloud services are considered "public" when they are delivered over the public Internet, and they may be offered as a paid subscription, or free of charge.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Architecturally, there are few differences between public- and private-cloud services, but security concerns increase substantially when services (applications, storage, and other resources) are shared by multiple customers.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Most public-cloud providers offer direct-connection services that allow customers to securely link their legacy data centers to their cloud-resident applications.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Several factors like the functionality of the solutions, cost, integrational and organizational aspects as well as safety & security are influencing the decision of enterprises and organizations to choose a public cloud or on-premises solution.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Varied use cases for hybrid cloud composition exist.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] For example, an organization may store sensitive client data in house on a private cloud application, but interconnect that application to a business intelligence application provided on a public cloud as a software service.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] This example of hybrid cloud extends the capabilities of the enterprise to deliver a specific business service through the addition of externally available public cloud services.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Hybrid cloud adoption depends on a number of factors such as data security and compliance requirements, level of control needed over data, and the applications an organization uses.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Another example of hybrid cloud is one where IT organizations use public cloud computing resources to meet temporary capacity needs that can not be met by the private cloud.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] This capability enables hybrid clouds to employ cloud bursting for scaling across clouds.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Cloud bursting is an application deployment model in which an application runs in a private cloud or data center and "bursts" to a public cloud when the demand for computing capacity increases.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] A primary advantage of cloud bursting and a hybrid cloud model is that an organization pays for extra compute resources only when they are needed.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Cloud bursting enables data centers to create an in-house IT infrastructure that supports average workloads, and use cloud resources from public or private clouds, during spikes in processing demands.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] As a result, only a portion of the potential cost savings of cloud computing is achieved.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] According to ISO/IEC 22123-1: "multi-cloud is a cloud deployment model in which a customer uses public cloud services provided by two or more cloud service providers".
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Poly cloud refers to the use of multiple public clouds for the purpose of leveraging specific services that each provider offers.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] It differs from Multi cloud in that it is not designed to increase flexibility or mitigate against failures but is rather used to allow an organization to achieve more than could be done with a single provider.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] According to International Data Corporation (IDC), global spending on cloud computing services has reached $706 billion and is expected to reach $1.3 trillion by 2025.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Gartner estimated that global public cloud services end-user spending would reach $600 billion by 2023.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] According to a McKinsey & Company report, cloud cost-optimization levers and value-oriented business use cases foresee more than $1 trillion in run-rate EBITDA across Fortune 500 companies as up for grabs in 2030.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] In 2022, more than $1.3 trillion in enterprise IT spending was at stake from the shift to the cloud, growing to almost $1.8 trillion in 2025, according to Gartner.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] The *Communication* set out a series of "digital agenda actions" which the Commission proposed to undertake in order to support the development of a fair and effective market for cloud computing services.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] As of 2025, the three largest cloud computing providers by market share, commonly referred to as hyperscalers, are Amazon Web Services (AWS), Microsoft Azure, and Google Cloud.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] These companies dominate the global cloud market due to their extensive infrastructure, broad service offerings, and scalability.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] In recent years, organizations have increasingly adopted alternative cloud providers, which offer specialized services that distinguish them from hyperscalers.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Alternative cloud providers are often part of multi-cloud strategies, where organizations use multiple cloud services—both from hyperscalers and specialized providers—to optimize performance, compliance, and cost efficiency.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] However, they do not necessarily serve as direct replacements for hyperscalers, as their offerings are typically more specialized.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] The goal of cloud computing is to allow users to take benefit from all of these technologies, without the need for deep knowledge about or expertise with each one of them.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] The cloud aims to cut costs and helps the users focus on their core business instead of being impeded by IT obstacles.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] The main enabling technology for cloud computing is virtualization.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Virtualization software separates a physical computing device into one or more "virtual" devices, each of which can be easily used and managed to perform computing tasks.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] With operating system-level virtualization essentially creating a scalable system of multiple independent computing devices, idle computing resources can be allocated and used more efficiently.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Virtualization provides the agility required to speed up IT operations and reduces cost by increasing infrastructure utilization.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Autonomic computing automates the process through which the user can provision resources on-demand.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] By minimizing user involvement, automation speeds up the process, reduces labor costs and reduces the possibility of human errors.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Cloud computing uses concepts from utility computing to provide metrics for the services used.
[src:heroku-platform/cloud-computing] Cloud computing attempts to address QoS (quality of service) and reliability problems of other grid computing models.
[src:heroku-platform/heroku] Heroku was initially developed by James Lindenbaum, Adam Wiggins, and Orion Henry for supporting projects that were compatible with the Ruby programming platform Rack.
[src:heroku-platform/heroku] The prototype development took around six months.
[src:heroku-platform/heroku] Later on, Heroku faced setbacks because of a lack of proper market customers as many app developers used their own tools and environment.
[src:heroku-platform/heroku] In January 2009, a new platform was launched which was built almost from scratch after a three-month effort.
[src:heroku-platform/heroku] In October 2009, Byron Sebastian joined Heroku as CEO.
[src:heroku-platform/heroku] On December 8, 2010, Salesforce.com acquired Heroku as a wholly owned subsidiary of Salesforce.com.
[src:heroku-platform/heroku] On July 12, 2011, Yukihiro "Matz" Matsumoto, the chief designer of the Ruby programming language, joined the company as Chief Architect for Ruby.
[src:heroku-platform/heroku] That same month, Heroku added support for Node.js and Clojure.
[src:heroku-platform/heroku] On September 15, 2011, Heroku and Facebook introduced Heroku for Facebook.
[src:heroku-platform/heroku] At present Heroku supports Redis databases in addition to its standard PostgreSQL.
[src:heroku-platform/heroku] On April 7, 2022, Heroku suffered a significant security intrusion when attackers were able to obtain an access token for a Heroku account that was used for automation purposes.
[src:heroku-platform/heroku] Heroku confirmed that the attack accessed OAuth bearer tokens used for integration with GitHub and salted and hashed customer passwords in May 2022.
[src:heroku-platform/heroku] The OAuth2 tokens were then used in targeted attacks against an unknown set of GitHub repositories apparently in an attempt to find secret tokens, where npm was the primary repository GitHub identified as a target.
[src:heroku-platform/heroku] It is unclear if the original source of the breach is known or not.
[src:heroku-platform/heroku] In August 2022, Heroku announced that its free plans would be discontinued, citing fraud and abuse as reasons for the change.
[src:heroku-platform/heroku] In March 2024 at Kubecon Paris, Heroku announced that it was replatforming onto Kubernetes.
[src:heroku-platform/heroku] On February 6, 2026, Heroku announced that it would be transitioning to a new engineering model with a focus on security, reliability, support and stability rather than introducing new features.
[src:heroku-platform/heroku] It mentioned that Enterprise Account contracts would no longer be offered to new users.
[src:heroku-platform/heroku] It has emphasised that Heroku remains fully supported and existing customers would not be affected by this change.
[src:heroku-platform/heroku] The name "Heroku" is a portmanteau of "heroic" and "haiku".
[src:heroku-platform/heroku] The Japanese theme is a nod to Matz for creating Ruby.
[src:heroku-platform/heroku] The creators of Heroku did not want the name of their project to have a particular meaning, in Japanese or any other language, and so chose to invent a name.
[src:heroku-platform/heroku] Applications that are run on Heroku typically have a unique domain used to route HTTP requests to the correct application container or *dyno.* Each of the dynos are spread across a "dyno grid" which consists of several servers.
[src:heroku-platform/heroku] Heroku's Git server handles application repository pushes from permitted users.
[src:heroku-platform/heroku] All Heroku services are hosted on Amazon's EC2 cloud-computing platform.
[src:heroku-platform/heroku] The Heroku network runs the customer's apps in virtual containers which execute on a reliable runtime environment.
[src:heroku-platform/heroku] These Dynos can run code written in Node, Ruby, PHP, Go, Scala, Python, Java, or Clojure.
[src:heroku-platform/heroku] Heroku also provides custom build packs with which the developer can deploy apps in any other language.
[src:heroku-platform/heroku] Heroku lets the developer scale the app instantly just by either increasing the number of dynos or by changing the type of dyno the app runs in.
[src:heroku-platform/heroku] Heroku Postgres provides features like continuous protection, rollback, and high availability; also forks, followers, and data clips.
[src:heroku-platform/heroku] from Heroku to provide a better developer experience.
[src:heroku-platform/heroku] It is fully managed and is provided as a service by Heroku.
[src:heroku-platform/heroku] It helps in managing instances with a CLI, associate data with Postgres to gain business insights using SQL tools, and lets customer gain performance visibility.
[src:heroku-platform/heroku] Heroku Teams is a team management tool which provides collaboration and controls to bring a customer's developers, processes, and tools together in order to build better software.
[src:heroku-platform/heroku] With Heroku Teams, teams can self-organize, add, and manage members, get fine-grained control with app-level permissions, and also use collaboration tools like Heroku Pipelines.
[src:heroku-platform/heroku] It also provides delegated administration and centralized billing.
[src:heroku-platform/heroku] Heroku Enterprise provides services to large companies which help them to improve collaboration among different teams.
[src:heroku-platform/heroku] It provides a set of features like fine-grained access controls, identity federation, and private spaces to manage their enterprise application development process, resources, and users.
[src:heroku-platform/heroku] This is done by having seamless data synchronization between Heroku Postgres databases and Salesforce organizations.
[src:heroku-platform/platform-as-a-service] The first public platform as a service was Zimki, launched by Fotango, a London-based company owned by Canon Europe.
[src:heroku-platform/platform-as-a-service] It was developed in 2005, had a beta launch in March 2006 and a public launch at EuroOSCON in 2006.
[src:heroku-platform/platform-as-a-service] At the time of its closure, Zimki had several thousand developer accounts.
[src:heroku-platform/platform-as-a-service] It had demonstrated the technical viability of Platform as a Service, but also provided the first example of the perils of being dependent on a single provider.
[src:heroku-platform/platform-as-a-service] The original intent of PaaS was to simplify the writing of code, with the infrastructure and operations handled by the PaaS provider.
[src:heroku-platform/platform-as-a-service] Originally, all PaaSes were in the public cloud.
[src:heroku-platform/platform-as-a-service] Because many companies did not want to have everything in the public cloud, private and hybrid PaaS options (managed by internal IT departments) were created.
[src:heroku-platform/platform-as-a-service] PaaS provides an environment for developers and companies to create, host and deploy applications, saving developers from the complexities of infrastructure (setting up, configuring and managing elements such as servers and databases).
[src:heroku-platform/platform-as-a-service] PaaS can improve the speed of developing an app, and allow its user to focus on the application itself.
[src:heroku-platform/platform-as-a-service] With PaaS, the customer manages applications and data, while the provider (in public PaaS) or IT department (in private PaaS) manages runtime, middleware, operating system, virtualization, servers, storage and networking.
[src:heroku-platform/platform-as-a-service] Development tools provided by the vendor are customized according to the needs of the user.
[src:heroku-platform/platform-as-a-service] The user can choose to maintain the software, or have the vendor maintain it.
[src:heroku-platform/platform-as-a-service] Besides the service engineering aspects, PaaS offerings include mechanisms for service management, such as monitoring, workflow management, discovery and reservation.
[src:heroku-platform/platform-as-a-service] Disadvantages of various PaaS providers as cited by their users include increased pricing at larger scales, lack of operational features, reduced control, and the difficulties of traffic routing systems.
[src:heroku-platform/platform-as-a-service] There are several types of PaaS, including public, private and hybrid.
[src:heroku-platform/platform-as-a-service] PaaS was originally intended for applications on public cloud services, before expanding to include private and hybrid options.
[src:heroku-platform/platform-as-a-service] Public PaaS is derived from software as a service (SaaS), and is situated in cloud computing between SaaS and infrastructure as a service (IaaS).
[src:heroku-platform/platform-as-a-service] SaaS is software hosted in the cloud so that it does not reside or run on customer computers.
[src:heroku-platform/platform-as-a-service] IaaS provides virtual hardware from a provider with adjustable scalability.
[src:heroku-platform/platform-as-a-service] In IaaS, the server is managed by the user, whereas in PaaS by the provider.
[src:heroku-platform/platform-as-a-service] A private PaaS can typically be downloaded and installed either in a company's on-premises data center, or in a public cloud.
[src:heroku-platform/platform-as-a-service] Once the software is installed on one or more machines, the private PaaS arranges the application and database components into a single hosting platform.
[src:heroku-platform/platform-as-a-service] Hybrid PaaS is typically a deployment consisting of a mix of public and private deployments.
[src:heroku-platform/platform-as-a-service] A communications platform as a service (CPaaS) is a cloud-based platform that enables developers to add real-time communications features (voice, video, and messaging) in their own applications without building back-end infrastructure and interfaces.
[src:heroku-platform/platform-as-a-service] Also, CPaaS and hardware and software specifications are specifically designed to support (tele)communications applications.
[src:heroku-platform/platform-as-a-service] These applications and their usage are much more sensitive to jitter, latency and packet losses.
[src:heroku-platform/platform-as-a-service] Hosted PBX, cellular networks, (near real-time) applications typically are deployed on CPaaS platforms.
[src:heroku-platform/platform-as-a-service] Initiated in 2012, mobile PaaS (mPaaS) provides development capabilities for mobile app designers and developers.
[src:heroku-platform/platform-as-a-service] The Yankee Group identified mPaaS as one of its themes for 2014.
[src:heroku-platform/platform-as-a-service] There are various types of PaaS providers.
[src:heroku-platform/platform-as-a-service] All offer application hosting and a deployment environment, along with various integrated services.
[src:heroku-platform/platform-as-a-service] Services offer varying levels of scalability and maintenance.
[src:heroku-platform/platform-as-a-service] Developers can write an application and upload it to a PaaS that supports their software language of choice, and the application runs on that PaaS.
[src:heroku-platform/platform-as-a-service] The UK Government encourages departments to make use of public cloud solutions as a first option.
[src:heroku-platform/platform-as-a-service] PaaS is in use within UK Government but the technology community within government notes that PaaS providers may restrict the software, languages and interfaces they are willing to support.
[src:heroku-platform/platform-as-a-service] The Government operated its own GOV.UK PaaS service from 2015 until 2023, but this has now been decommissioned.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] Deployment can involve activities on the producer (software developer) side or on the consumer (user) side or both.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] Deployment to consumers is a hard task because the target systems are diverse and unpredictable.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] Software as a service avoids these difficulties by deploying only to dedicated servers that are typically under the producer's control.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] Because every software system is unique, the precise processes or procedures within each activity can hardly be defined.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] Therefore, "deployment" should be interpreted as a *general process* that has to be customized according to specific requirements or characteristics.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] When computers were extremely large, expensive, and bulky (mainframes and minicomputers), the software was often bundled together with the hardware by manufacturers and provided for free.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] A pivotal moment occurred in 1969 when IBM, influenced by antitrust lawsuits, began charging for software and services separately from hardware.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] This "unbundling" effectively created the modern software industry, turning software into a commercial product.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] Early deployment processes were highly structured; the Lincoln Labs Phased Model, developed in 1956 for the SAGE air defense system, introduced sequential phases that influenced later methodologies.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] This approach was formalized in the waterfall model, which became dominant after being described by Winston Royce in 1970.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] It led to infrequent, costly, and lengthy release cycles, often taking years.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] If business software needed to be installed, it often required an expensive, time-consuming visit by a systems architect or a consultant.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] For complex, on-premises installation of enterprise software today, this is sometimes still the case.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] The development of mass-market software for the new age of microcomputers in the 1980s brought new forms of software distribution – first cartridges, then Compact Cassettes, then floppy disks, and later (in the 1990s and beyond) optical media, the internet and flash drives.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] This shift meant that software deployment could be left to the customer.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] During this period, alternatives to the rigid waterfall model emerged.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] The Spiral Model, proposed by Barry Boehm in 1988, introduced a risk-driven, iterative approach that challenged waterfall's linear structure and paved the way for more flexible, agile methodologies.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] As customer-led deployment became standard, it was recognized that configuration should be user-friendly.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] In the 1990s, tools like InstallShield became popular, providing installer wizards that eliminated the need for users to perform complex tasks like editing registry entries.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] In pre-internet software deployments, releases were by nature expensive and infrequent affairs.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] The spread of the internet fundamentally transformed software distribution and made end-to-end agile software development viable by enabling rapid collaboration and digital delivery.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] The foundations for modern rapid deployment were laid in the 1990s when Kent Beck developed Continuous Integration as a core practice of Extreme Programming, advocating for developers to integrate their work daily.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] The advent of cloud computing and software as a service (SaaS) in the 2000s further accelerated this trend, allowing software to be deployed to a large number of customers in minutes.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] This shift also meant deployment schedules were now typically determined by the software supplier, not the customers.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] Such flexibility led to the rise of continuous delivery as a viable option, especially for web applications.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] Modern deployment strategies that build upon these principles include blue–green deployment and canary release deployment.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] process and is sometimes classified as part of the development process rather than deployment process.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] and transfer to the computer system(s) on which it will be run in production.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] required for the system to operate with tolerable performance and planning and/or documenting subsequent activities of the deployment process.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] for executing the software (manually or automatically).
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] and/or making all the required subsystems ready to use.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] , the main copy of the software to be used by users - "production" - might be installed on a production server in a production environment.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] ), or even be gradually rolled out in parallel to different groups of customers, with the possibility of canceling one or more of the parallel deployments.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] Deactivation is the inverse of activation and refers to shutting down any already-executing components of a system.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] Deactivation is often required to perform other deployment activities, e.g., a software system may need to be deactivated before an update can be performed.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] Uninstallation is the inverse of installation.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] It is the removal of a system that is no longer required.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] The update process replaces an earlier version of all or part of a software system with a newer release.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] It commonly consists of deactivation followed by installation.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] , the old version of a software application is typically also uninstalled as an automatic part of the process.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] Automation of these update processes ranges from fully automatic to user-initiated and controlled.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] is an example of a system with a semi-automatic method for retrieving and installing updates to both the antivirus definitions and other components of the system.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] Other software products provide query mechanisms for determining when updates are available.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] Version tracking systems help the user find and install updates to software systems.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] For example: The Software Catalog stores the version and other information for each software package installed on a local system.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] One-click of a button launches a browser window to the upgrade web page for the application, including auto-filling of the user name and password for sites that require a login.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] so the process can be configured to be fully automated.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] Some third-party software also supports automated version tracking and upgrading for certain Windows software packages.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] The complexity and variability of software products have fostered the emergence of specialized roles for coordinating and engineering the deployment process.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] For desktop systems, end-users frequently also become the "software deployers" when they install a software package on their machine.
[src:heroku-platform/software-deployment] The deployment of enterprise software involves many more roles, and those roles typically change as the application progresses from the test (pre-production) to production environments.
[src:heroku-platform/twelve-factor-app-methodology] The **Twelve-Factor App methodology** is a methodology for building software-as-a-service applications.
[src:heroku-platform/twelve-factor-app-methodology] These best practices are designed to enable applications to be built with portability and resilience when deployed to the web.
[src:heroku-platform/twelve-factor-app-methodology] The methodology was drafted by developers at Heroku, a platform-as-a-service company, and was first presented by Adam Wiggins circa 2011.
[src:heroku-platform/twelve-factor-app-methodology] An Nginx architect argued that the relevance of the Twelve-Factor app concept is somewhat specific to Heroku, while introducing their own (Nginx's) proposed architecture for microservices.
[src:heroku-platform/twelve-factor-app-methodology] The twelve factors are however cited as a baseline from which to adapt or extend.
